      "response": "Perfect! Now I have all the information I need to provide a complete diagnosis. Let me write up my findings:\n\n## ROOT CAUSE\n\n**File:** `libyara/parser.c:733`\n\nThe code checks for duplicate identifiers when declaring a rule by looking in both `rules_table` and `objects_table`. However, there's a namespace mismatch:\n\n- **Rules** are stored in `rules_table` with the current namespace: `compiler->current_namespace->name`\n- **Variables (objects)** are stored in `objects_table` with global scope: `NULL` (as evidenced by `_yr_compiler_define_variable` in compiler.c:915)\n\nThe buggy code incorrectly uses `compiler->current_namespace->name` when looking up variables in `objects_table`:\n\n```c\nif (yr_hash_table_lookup(\n      compiler->rules_table,\n      identifier,\n      compiler->current_namespace->name) != NULL ||\n    yr_hash_table_lookup(\n      compiler->objects_table,\n      identifier,\n      compiler->current_namespace->name) != NULL)  // BUG: should be NULL\n```\n\nSince variables are stored with namespace `NULL`, the lookup with `compiler->current_namespace->name` fails to find them, causing the duplicate identifier check to fail silently. The test expects `ERROR_DUPLICATED_IDENTIFIER` (14) but gets 0 because `compiler->last_error` is never set.\n\n## LOCAL FIX\n\nChange line 733 in `libyara/parser.c` from:\n```c\ncompiler->current_namespace->name) != NULL)\n```\nto:\n```c\nNULL) != NULL)\n```\n\nThis makes the lookup use the correct namespace for variables (global scope).\n\n## GLOBAL FIX\n\nCreate a helper function or add clarifying documentation that distinguishes namespace-scoped identifiers (rules) from globally-scoped identifiers (variables). Optionally, add compile-time assertions or checks to ensure that whenever checking for identifier collisions across different tables, the appropriate namespace is used for each table type. Better yet, consider whether this dual-namespace system is the right long-term design, or if variables should also be namespace-scoped to match rules.",
